    <h1>Inheritance in Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)</h1>
    <p>
        <strong>Inheritance</strong> is a concept in OOP that allows one class to reuse the code of another class.  
        The class that provides its properties and methods is called the <strong>parent class</strong> (or base class), and the class that receives these properties and methods is called the <strong>child class</strong> (or derived class).  
        This helps reduce code duplication and makes it easier to manage.
    </p>

    <h2>Parent and Child Classes</h2>
    <p>Think of it like a family tree:</p>

    <div class="diagram-container">
        <div class="class-box parent">
            <strong>Person (Parent Class)</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Name</li>
                <li>Age</li>
                <li>Introduce()</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="class-box child">
            <strong>Student (Child Class)</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Name (inherited)</li>
                <li>Age (inherited)</li>
                <li>Introduce() (inherited)</li>
                <li>School</li>
                <li>Study()</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p>
        In this diagram, <strong>Student</strong> is a child class that inherits from the <strong>Person</strong> parent class.  
        The child class automatically has the properties <strong>Name</strong> and <strong>Age</strong> and the method <strong>Introduce()</strong> from the parent class.  
        It also adds its own property <strong>School</strong> and method <strong>Study()</strong>.
    </p>

    <h2>Example: Basic Inheritance</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Base and Derived Classes</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public class Person
{
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public int Age { get; set; }

    public void Introduce()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"Hello, my name is {Name} and I am {Age} years old.");
    }
}

public class Student : Person
{
    public string School { get; set; }

    public void Study()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"{Name} is studying at {School}.");
    }
}

// Usage
Student student = new Student();
student.Name = "Alice";
student.Age = 20;
student.School = "MIT";

student.Introduce();
student.Study();
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p>
        Here’s what happens step by step:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Student student = new Student();</strong> – creates a new object of the child class.</li>
        <li><strong>student.Name</strong> and <strong>student.Age</strong> – inherited from the parent class <strong>Person</strong>.</li>
        <li><strong>student.Introduce()</strong> – calls the method from the parent class.</li>
        <li><strong>student.School</strong> and <strong>student.Study()</strong> – defined in the child class itself.</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Expected Output:</strong></p>
    <pre>
Hello, my name is Alice and I am 20 years old.
Alice is studying at MIT.
    </pre>

    <h2>Key Points About Inheritance</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>A child class inherits all accessible members from the parent class.</li>
        <li>You can add new properties or methods in the child class to extend functionality.</li>
        <li>The <code>base</code> keyword lets a child class access parent members explicitly.</li>
        <li>C# allows single inheritance for classes, meaning a class can have only one parent class.</li>
        <li>Inheritance reduces code duplication and makes your code more organized.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        Note: Inheritance is a key OOP concept and will also appear in advanced topics, especially when combined with polymorphism and interfaces.
    </p>

